{"title_page": "WCPT (AM)", "text_new": "{{short description|Progressive talk radio station in Willow Springs\u2013Chicago, Illinois}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name = WCPT\n| image = WCPT station logo.PNG\n| city = [[Willow Springs, Illinois]]\n| area = [[Chicago metropolitan area]]\n| branding = '''WCPT 820'''\n| slogan = Chicago's Progressive Talk\n| airdate = {{start date and age|1923|6|23}}\n| frequency = 820 [[Kilohertz|kHz]]\n| former_callsigns = WCBD (1923&ndash;41)<br>WAIT (1941&ndash;86)<br>WCZE (1986&ndash;88)<br>WXEZ (1988&ndash;90)<br>WPNT (1990&ndash;92)<br>WSCR (1992&ndash;97)<br>WYPA (1997&ndash;2001)<br>WCSN (2001&ndash;05)<br>WAIT (2005&ndash;07)\n| former_frequencies = 870 kHz (1923&ndash;28)<br>1080 kHz (1928&ndash;41)<br>1110 kHz (1941)\n| format = [[progressive talk radio|Progressive Talk]]\n| power = 5,800 [[watt]]s (day)<br>2,500 watts (auxiliary day)<br>1,500 watts (night)\n| class = B\n| facility_id = 16849\n| coordinates = {{nowrap|{{coord|41|58|53|N|87|46|20|W|}} (day)}}<br>{{nowrap|{{coord|41|32|30|N|88|2|3|W}} (night/aux)}}\n| owner = [[Newsweb Corporation]]\n| licensee = WYPA, Inc.\n| webcast = [http://player.tritondigital.com/6111 Listen Live]\n| website = {{url|wcpt820.com}}\n| affiliations = [[Westwood One (current)|Westwood One]]<br>[[Pacifica Radio]]<br>[[Associated Press|AP Radio News]]\n| callsign_meaning = \"We're Chicago's Progressive Talk\"\n| sister_stations = [[WAIT (AM)|WAIT]], [[WCPY]], [[WNDZ]], [[WSBC]]\n}}\n\n'''WCPT''' (820 [[AM broadcasting|AM]]) \u2013 branded '''WCPT 820''' \u2013 is a commercial [[progressive talk radio|progressive talk]] [[Radio broadcasting|radio station]] licensed to [[Willow Springs, Illinois|Willow Springs]], [[Illinois]]. Owned by the [[Newsweb Corporation]], the station serves the [[Chicago metropolitan area]]. WCPT is the [[Chicago]] affiliate for [[Pacifica Foundation|Pacifica Radio]], ''[[The Stephanie Miller Show]]'', ''[[Democracy Now!]]'' and ''[[The David Pakman Show]]'', in addition to syndicated personalities [[Thom Hartmann]] and [[Rick Ungar]]; and is the radio home of [[Santita Jackson]]. The studios and daytime transmitter are located in the [[Jefferson Park, Chicago|Jefferson Park]] neighborhood on Chicago's [[Northwest Side, Chicago|Northwest Side]], while the nighttime transmitter resides in nearby [[Joliet, Illinois|Joliet]].<ref name=\"FCC1\">[https://transition.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/amq?list=0&facid=16849 AM Query Results: WCPT], fcc.gov. Retrieved January 4, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"License\" /> Besides a standard [[analog transmission]], WCPT's programming is available online.\n\n==History==\n===WCBD===\nOn June 23, 1923, the station signed on using the call sign WCBD, broadcasting at 870 [[kilocycle]]s.<ref name=\"CoC\">Hearings Before the [[United States Senate Committee on Interstate Commerce]]. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=dIHNAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA127&lpg=PA127#v=onepage&q&f=false Commission on Communications]''. [[United States Government Publishing Office|United States Government Print Office]]. May 8, 1929. p. 126-129. Retrieved August 24, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Kneitel\">\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Popular-Communications/80s/Popular-Communications-1986-06.pdf WCBD, The \"Flat Earth\" Radio Station]\", ''[[Popular Communications]]''. June 1986. p. 31-34. Retrieved October 1, 2018.</ref> The station was located in [[Zion, Illinois]], and was owned by [[Wilbur Glenn Voliva]], who was the \"General Overseer\" of the [[Christian Catholic Apostolic Church]], and was known for his [[flat Earth]] beliefs.<ref name=\"CoC\"/><ref name=\"Kneitel\"/><ref name=\"HistoryCards\">[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/getimportletter_exh.cgi?import_letter_id=46665 History Cards for WCPT], fcc.gov. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref> WCBD was non-commercial, airing [[Christian radio|religious programming]] that reflected Voliva's viewpoints.<ref name=\"Kneitel\"/> The station originally ran at 500 watts.<ref name=\"CoC\"/> On July 14, 1924, its power was increased to 5,000 watts.<ref name=\"CoC\"/> From April 1924 until November 11, 1928, WCBD shared time on its frequency with [[WLS (AM)|WLS]].<ref name=\"CoC\"/><ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/>  In November 1928, its frequency was changed to 1080&nbsp;kHz, where it shared time with [[WMBI (AM)|WMBI]].<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/><ref name=\"CoC\"/>\n\nIn 1936, the station was sold to Gene T. Dyer.<ref name=\"Kneitel\"/> It became a [[commercial radio|commercial]] operation, and aired religious, ethnic, and music programming.<ref name=\"Kneitel\"/><ref>''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-Guide/1937/Radio-Guide-37-05-15.pdf Radio Guide]''. Week ending May 15, 1937. Retrieved October 1, 2018.</ref><ref>''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-Guide/1938/Radio-Guide-38-01-15.pdf Radio Guide]''. Week ending January 15, 1938. Retrieved October 1, 2018.</ref> On April 2, 1937, the station's transmitter and the Christian Catholic Apostolic Church's Shiloh Tabernacle were destroyed in a fire set by a teenager who believed Voliva had swindled his father.<ref>\"[https://newspaperarchive.com/cumberland-evening-times-apr-05-1937-p-1/ Youth Confesses to Firing Tabernacle]\", ''Cumberland Evening Times''. April 5, 1937. p. 1. Retrieved October 1, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Kneitel\"/> Its transmitter site was relocated to [[Addison Township, DuPage County, Illinois|Addison Township]], in what today is part of [[Elmhurst, Illinois]].<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> WCBD shared WMBI's transmitter while its new transmitter was being built.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> Its frequency was changed to 1110&nbsp;kHz in March 1941, as a result of the [[North American Regional Broadcasting Agreement]].<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/>\n\n===WAIT===\nIn 1941, the station's frequency was changed to 820 kHz.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> It ran 5,000 watts, signing off at sunset in [[Dallas]] to protect [[WBAP (AM)|WBAP]] in [[Fort Worth]].<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/>  The call sign was changed to WAIT.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> From 1947 to 1959, the station shared time on Sundays with a new WCBD in [[Zion, Illinois]], which operated on Sundays only.<ref name=\"Kneitel\"/><ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1959/1959-05-25-BC.pdf Media reports]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]]''. May 25, 1959. p. 79. Retrieved October 1, 2018.</ref> In 1948, [[Daddy-O Daylie]] began his radio career on WAIT, hosting a [[jazz]] program on the station.<ref>\"[http://www.thehistorymakers.org/biography/holmes-daddy-o-daylie Holmes 'Daddy-O' Daylie]\", ''The History Makers''. May 29, 2001. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref><ref>Heim, Chris. \"[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1989-02-12-8903040739-story.html Radio Roots]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. February 12, 1989. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> In 1954, the station was sold to Robert Oscar Miller and family.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1954/1954-10-04-BC.pdf Our Respects to Robert Oscar Miller]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting/Telecasting]]''. October 4, 1954. p. 20. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref> In the 1950s, WAIT published a chart of the top 20 popular songs in Chicago.<ref>''[http://las-solanas.com/surveys/WAIT/WAIT_1956-12-24_1.jpg WAIT Platter Pulse]'', WAIT. December 24, 1956. Retrieved October 1, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn 1962, the station was sold to a partnership led by Maurice and Lois Rosenfield, for $1 million.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1962/1962-07-02-BC.pdf Changing hands]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]]''. July 2, 1962. p. 44. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"OConnor\"/> The station adopted a [[beautiful music]] format, which it continued to air through the 1970s.<ref name=\"OConnor\">O'Connor, Richard. (2009). ''[http://www.percyfaithpages.org/A%20Brief%20History%20of%20Beautiful%20Music%20Radio.pdf A Brief History of Beautiful Music Radio]'', Percy Faith Pages. Retrieved September 30, 2018.</ref><ref>\"[https://books.google.com/books?id=SyAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA34#v=onepage&q&f=false Stations By Format]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. October 31, 1964. p. 34. Retrieved January 20, 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://books.google.com/books?id=8TkhAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA2-PA56#v=onepage&q&f=false Catalog of Copyright Entries: Third Series]\", Volume 20, Part 6, Number 1; Maps and Atlases, January - June 1966; ''[[United States Copyright Office|Copyright Office]] - [[Library of Congress|The Library of Congress]]'', [[Washington DC]]: 1967. pp. 56-57. Retrieved September 30, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"79Trib\">\"[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Station-Albums/Chicago-Trib-1979-Mar-About-Chi-Radio.pdf Stations, everywhere: a listeners' guide to the AM and FM bands]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune Magazine]]''. March 4, 1979. p. 34. Retrieved September 30, 2018.</ref> In 1978, WAIT briefly switched to an all talk format, before returning to the beautiful music format it had long aired.<ref name=\"79Trib\"/> In 1979, the station was sold to Century Broadcasting.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1979/BC-1979-05-14.pdf Ownership Changes]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]]''. May 14, 1979. p. 72-73. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref> In 1980, it applied to the [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) for a [[construction permit]] to add nighttime operations at 1,000 watts.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> The station added nighttime operations in 1982, and ran 5,000 watts during the day and 1,000 watts at night.<ref>[http://www.fuzzymemories.tv/index.php?c=1139 WAIT AM 82 - \"Nice 'N Easy Music\"], The Museum of Classic Chicago Television. Retrieved September 30, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"BCYearbook1983\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1983/B-Radio-Ala-Mt-1983-YB.pdf Broadcasting/Cablecasting Yearbook 1983]'', [[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting/Cablecasting]], 1983. p. B-70. Retrieved September 30, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn October 1982, WAIT began airing an [[adult standards]] format branded \"Great Hits\", featuring the hits of the 1940s, 1950s, and 1960s.<ref>Alridge, Ron. \"'Saturday Night' in its death throes?\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. October 18, 1982. Section 2, p. 12.</ref><ref>[[Eric Zorn|Zorn, Eric]]. \"WJJD vs. WAIT: Sounds of war have a big band beat\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. February 20, 1984. pp. 1, 3.</ref><ref>\"[https://books.google.com/books?id=XiQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT14#v=onepage&q&f=false 'Great Hits' Readied for Syndication]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. November 13, 1982. p. 15. Retrieved September 30, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"ChiRadioGuide\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Other-Documments/Chicago_Magazine/Chicago-Radio-Guide-May-1985.pdf Chicago Radio Guide]''. Vol. 1, No. 1. May 1985. Retrieved September 30, 2018.</ref> The station aired ''[[Chuck Schaden]]'s Radio Theatre'' weekday evenings.<ref name=\"ChiRadioGuide\" /> [[Eddie Hubbard]] joined WAIT in 1983, and hosted the morning drive show.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1983/BC-1983-07-%2004.pdf Programming]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable]]''. July 4, 1983. p. 101. Retrieved April 27, 2020.</ref><ref>[[Eric Zorn|Zorn, Eric]]. \"On the radio: Hellyer shoots for old stars\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. February 16, 1984. Section 5, p. 13.</ref>\n\n===Soft AC era===\nOn April 7, 1986, the station began airing a [[Soft Adult Contemporary]] format as \"Cozy\" WCZE, delivered by satellite from [[Transtar Radio Networks]]' \"Format 41\" service.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"'Night owl' Schwartz flaps over split in shift at WGN\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. April 8, 1986. p. 50.</ref><ref name=\"BossTrib\">Boss, Kit; \"[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1986-07-17/features/8602200802_1_satellite-music-network-satellite-programming-affiliate-stations Radio`s Satellite Networks Beam With Success]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. July 17, 1986. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> In April 1988, its call sign was changed to WXEZ, standing for \"Extra Easy\", and it became a [[simulcast]] of [[WSHE-FM|WXEZ-FM]], airing [[easy listening]] music.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"For 'beautiful music' stations, 'EZ' does it\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. April 18, 1988. p. 33.</ref><ref name=\"RadioWaves\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Other-Documments/City-Magazines-Misc/Chicagoland-Radio-Waves-Two-Issues.pdf Chicagoland Radio Waves]'', MediaTies. Summer 1988. Retrieved September 30, 2018.</ref> In 1989, it shifted back to a soft AC format, playing more vocals and fewer instrumentals.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1980s/1989/RR-1989-08-18.pdf WXEZ Moving To Soft AC]\", ''[[Radio & Records]]''. August 18, 1989. pp. 5, 38. Retrieved September 30, 2018.</ref> On November 16, 1990, the station's call sign was changed to WPNT, and it briefly aired a [[hot AC]] format branded \"The Point,\" simulcasting WPNT-FM.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4026716.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505110553/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4026716.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=May 5, 2016|title=To make its 'Point,' 'XEZ will disappear|last=Feder|first=Robert|date=November 15, 1990|newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref> In early January 1991, the station was taken off the air, as its owner disposed of its transmitter site in Elmhurst, Illinois.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"'Zoned' news bits - Ch. 5 to add daily cable cut-ins for suburbs\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. January 3, 1991. p. 53.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-M-Street/M-Street-Journal/M-Street-1991-01.pdf Format Changes]\", ''The M Street Journal''. Vol. 8, No. 1. January 7, 1991. p. 1. Retrieved October 1, 2018.</ref>\n\n===The Score===\n[[File:Former studios of WSCR and WXRT.jpg|thumb|Former studio and transmitter site in Chicago's Cragin neighborhood]]\nIn late 1991, the station was sold to Diamond Broadcasting.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1991/BC-1991-10-14.pdf New All-Sports AM Set for Chicago Debut]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]]''. October 14, 1991. p. 39. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref> On January 2, 1992, it returned to the air from a new site in Chicago's [[Belmont Cragin, Chicago|Cragin]] neighborhood, though without nighttime operations.<ref>[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/comment.pl?Application_id=159584&File_number=BP-19910429AH Public Notice Comment], fcc.gov. Retrieved December 23, 2018.</ref> It became [[WSCR]] \"The Score,\" the first [[sports radio|all-sports station]] in Chicago.<ref>\"[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1990s/1992/RR-1992-01-03.pdf Street Talk]\", ''[[Radio & Records]]'', January 3, 1992. p. 20. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"KickOff\">[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20160505112238/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4088376.html Sports talk station will kick off Jan. 2]\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. December 24, 1991. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> The Score's original hosts included Tom Shaer, [[Dan Jiggetts]] partnered with [[Mike North]], and Dan McNeil.<ref name=\"KickOff\"/> McNeil would later be partnered with [[Terry Boers]].<ref name=\"ScoreHistory\">\"[https://chicago.cbslocal.com/2012/01/03/history-of-the-score-chapter-2/ History Of The Score: Chapter II \u2013 The AM 820 Years]\", [[WBBM-TV|CBS 2 Chicago]]. January 3, 2012. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> Former [[Chicago Bears]] coach [[Mike Ditka]] hosted a weekly show in 1992, and served as an analyst during football season until 1997, when he was hired to coach the [[New Orleans Saints]].<ref name=\"ScoreHistory\"/><ref>[[George Castle (journalist)|Castle, George]] (2006). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=1ANDhC9VbuwC&pg=PA224#v=onepage&q&f=false Baseball and the Media: How Fans Lose in Today's Coverage of the Game]''. [[University of Nebraska Press]]. p. 224. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> In 1995, the station was sold to [[Westinghouse Broadcasting|Group W]], along with [[WXRT]], for $60 million.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1990s/1995/RR-1995-04-21.pdf First- Quarter Trading Up 26%]\", ''[[Radio & Records]]''. April 21, 1995. p. 8. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref> On April 7, 1997, at 2:30 PM, \"The Score\" moved to [[WYLL|1160 AM]].<ref name=\"NewStation\">{{citenews|last=Feder|first=Robert|author-link=Robert Feder|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4395757.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207122515/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4395757.html|title=New station joins Chicago radio dial|newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=April 8, 1997|accessdate=January 27, 2019|archivedate=February 7, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>Hirsley, Michael. \"[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1997-04-04-9704040029-story.html Demand for Ditka May Bring Saints to Chicago - On Radio]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. April 4, 1997. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref>\n\n===WYPA===\nIn early 1997, the station was sold to N. John Douglas's Personal Achievement Radio, Inc. for $7.5 million.<ref>Rathburn, Elizabeth A. \"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1996/BC-1996-11-18.pdf Westinghouse/Infinity make Dallas Trust]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable]]''. November 16, 1996. p. 43. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1997/BC-1997-02-03.pdf Station & Cable Trading]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable]]''. February 3, 1997. p. 48. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref><ref>[https://licensing.fcc.gov/prod/cdbs/pubacc/Auth_Files/238891.pdf Consent to Assignment], fcc.gov. February 26, 1997. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref> On April 7, 1997, it began airing a motivational talk format as \"Personal Achievement Radio\", and its call sign was changed to WYPA.<ref name=\"NewStation\" /> On June 9, 1998, \"Personal Achievement Radio\" moved to [[WNDZ]], and WYPA adopted a Spanish language talk format as an affiliate of \"Radio Unica.\"<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"Soap opera channel to get trial run here\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. June 9, 1998. p. 37.</ref><ref name=\"MStreet61098\">\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-M-Street/M-Street-Journal/M-Street-1998-06.pdf Format Changes & Updates]\", ''The M-Street Journal''. June 10, 1998. Vol. 15 No. 23. p. 1. Retrieved April 28, 2020.</ref> Personalities heard on Radio Unica included [[Pedro Sevcec]], [[Isabel G\u00f3mez-Bassols]], among others.<ref>Sayewitz, Ronni. \"[https://www.bizjournals.com/dallas/stories/1998/06/01/newscolumn1.html Radio Unica hits Metroplex with Spanish all-talk format]\", ''[[Dallas Business Journal]]''. June 1, 1998. Retrieved June 30, 2019.</ref> In 1998, the station's owner, Achievement Radio Holdings, merged with Z-Spanish Media.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1998/BC-1998-07-06.pdf Z-Spanish merging with Achievement Radio Holdings]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable]]''. July 6, 1998. p. 48. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref> On May 15, 1999, Radio Unica moved to 950 [[WNTD]], though it continued to simulcast on WYPA.<ref name=\"Feder51499\">[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"3 radio stations find new spots on the dial\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. May 14, 1999. p. 57.</ref><ref name=\"OneonOne\">Kirk, Jim. \"[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-02-24/business/9902240249_1_radio-unica-one-on-one-sports-station One-On-One Sports Soon Zero For One On AM]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. February 24, 1999. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"MStreet51999\">\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-M-Street/M-Street-Journal/M-Street-1999-05.pdf Format Changes & Updates]\", ''The M Street Journal''. Vol. 16 No. 20. May 19, 1999. p. 2. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> In mid-1999, the station was purchased by Catholic Family Radio for $10.5 million, and on June 9 it began airing a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] talk format.<ref>Kirk, Jim. \"[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-06-27/business/9906270160_1_catholic-family-radio-howard-stern-christian-radio Catholic Radio CEO Keeps The Faith About Family Programming]\", ''Chicago Tribune''. June 27, 1999. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"MStreet62399\">\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-M-Street/M-Street-Journal/M-Street-1999-06.pdf Elsewhere]\", ''The M Street Journal''. Vol. 16, No. 25. June 23, 1999. p. 10. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"MStreet51999\" /><ref>Kirk, Jim. \"[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-05-18/business/0005180047_1_stations-catholic-family-radio-nba-lottery Investor May Rescue Catholic Radio]\", ''Chicago Tribune''. May 18, 2000. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> In April 2000, Catholic Family Radio placed all of its radio stations up for sale, and on May 29, Catholic Family Radio's programming was replaced by [[EWTN Radio]].<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"WBEE-AM will toast 45 years with concert\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. May 30, 2000. p. 37.</ref>\n\n===Newsweb ownership===\n[[File:WCPT's studio building and daytime tower.jpg|thumb|180px|WCPT's studio building and daytime tower]]\nIn early 2001, WYPA was purchased by Newsweb for $10.5 million.<ref>\"[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2001-02-25-0102250533-story.html Hallelujah Chorus]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. February 25, 2001. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> Newsweb's owner, [[Fred Eychaner]], is a significant donor to [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] causes.<ref>Harris, Melissa. \"[http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-xpm-2014-05-01-ct-eychaner-lockett-confidential-0501-biz-20140501-story.html Attention-shy Democratic donor Fred Eychaner opens up]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. May 1, 2014. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Zorn\" />\n\nOn March 1, 2001, [[One on One Sports]] (now known as [[SB Nation Radio]]) moved its programming from [[WAWE|WJKL]] to WYPA, and the station adopted a sports format.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.djheadlines.com/index.php?pid=103|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040514064033/http://www.djheadlines.com/index.php?pid=103|title=Chicago Media Headlines - February|website=DJ Headlines|date=February 26, 2001|archive-date=May 14, 2004|accessdate=October 2, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"MStreet22801\">\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-M-Street/M-Street-Journal/M-Street-2001-02.pdf M Street Bazaar]\", ''The M Street Journal''. Vol. 18, No. 09. February 28, 2001. p. 9. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Feder22201\">Feder, Robert. \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20131031162411/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4586434.html One-on-One sports talk goes to WYPA March 1]\", ''[[Chicago Sun Times]]''. February 22, 2001. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> On March 26, 2001, One-on-One Sports' name was changed to Sporting News Radio, and the station's call sign was changed to WCSN.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"Fox drops Murciano as noon news anchor\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. March 23, 2001. p. 55.</ref><ref name=\"CallSign\" /> Personalities heard on the station included [[Jay Mariotti]],<ref>De Luca, Chris. \"Sox' skid is over - But trade speculation overshadows victory\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. May 25, 2001. p. 96.</ref> [[Chet Coppock]],<ref>[[Chet Coppock|Coppock, Chet]]. \"Simply the Best - When all is said and done, Bears-Packers rivalry has no equal, writes Chet Coppock\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. November 11, 2001. p. 130.</ref> [[Phil Jackson]],<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"Channel 2's weather adds too much hot air\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. February 8, 2002. p. 57.</ref> [[Chet Coppock]],<ref>[[Irv Kupcinet|Kupcinet, Irv]]. \"Kup's Column\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. September 5, 2002. p. 46.</ref> and [[Bruce Murray (sportscaster)|Bruce Murray]].<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"Should politicians help journalists fight battles?\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. July 24, 2002. p. 67.</ref>\n\nIn April 2003, [[Starboard Broadcasting]] began leasing two hours of airtime a day to air the [[Relevant Radio]] Catholic network.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"Who'll sweep the market in May? Just stay tuned\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. April 23, 2003. p. 73.</ref> On December 1, 2003, it began leasing the entire day.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"Catholic network puts faith in radio market\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. November 20, 2003. p. 71.</ref>  On May 3, 2005, the station's call letters were changed back to WAIT when [[WAIT (AM)|WAIT (850 AM)]] launched progressive talk with the new call letters WCPT.<ref name=\"CallSign\">[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=16849&Callsign=WCPT Call Sign History], fcc.gov. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Moveto820\">\"[https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/32466/wcpt-chicago-to-move-to-820-am WCPT/Chicago To Move To 820 AM]\", ''All Access Music Group''. November 8, 2007. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Zorn\">[[Eric Zorn|Zorn, Eric]]. \"[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2005-05-03-0505030001-story.html 'Air America' return may not be a good thing]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. May 2, 2005. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> In October 2007, Relevant Radio moved to WNTD, though it continued to simulcast on WAIT until November 25.<ref name=\"Split\">[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"[https://www.pressreader.com/usa/chicago-sun-times/20071024/282815006882610 Split Personality]\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. October 24, 2007. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref><ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"[https://www.pressreader.com/usa/chicago-sun-times/20071102/282845071657903 Suddenly Santa]\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. November 2, 2007. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref>\n\n====Chicago's Progressive Talk====\nOn November 26, 2007, Chicago's Progressive Talk moved from 850 AM to 820 AM, doubling its power and providing coverage to all of the Chicago metropolitan area.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"'Fix' is finished - Emmis pulls the plug on Q101.1's bold morning show after 14 months\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. November 9, 2007. p. 63.</ref><ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"Meter's stuck - Arbitron bows to industry complaints by delaying new radio ratings system\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. November 27, 2007. p. 47.</ref><ref name=\"Moveto820\"/> The WCPT call letters moved along with the format to 820 AM, and the WAIT call letters returned to 850 AM.<ref name=\"Moveto820\"/><ref name=\"CallSign\"/><ref>[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=53504&Callsign=WAIT Call Sign History], fcc.gov. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> Hosts included [[Ed Schultz]], [[Stephanie Miller]], [[Randi Rhodes]], [[Thom Hartmann]], [[Bill Press]], and [[Robert F. Kennedy Jr.]]<ref>Knight, Bill. \"Broadcaster AM 820 broadens range of voices\", ''[[Pekin Daily Times]]''. December 7, 2007.</ref><ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"Liberal talker forms post-Franken ticket\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. February 7, 2007. p. 63.</ref><ref>[[Phil Rosenthal|Rosenthal, Phil]]. \"[https://newsblogs.chicagotribune.com/towerticker/2008/10/air-america-con.html 'Nine FM' consolidates -- who's left?]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. October 18, 2008. Retrieved April 29, 2020.</ref><ref name=\"LaunchNet\"/> On May 19, 2008, WCPT began airing ''[[The Rachel Maddow Show (radio program)|The Rachel Maddow Show]]''.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"Radio Rachel - MSNBC's star political analyst brings talk show back to WCPT\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. May 16, 2008. p. 49.</ref>\n\nOn March 29, 2008, [[Jake Hartford]] joined WCPT, hosting Saturday mornings.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"It's just Jake - Hartford finds happy landing as Saturday morning host at WCPT\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. November 9, 2007. p. 63.</ref> In late October 2008, the station started simulcasting on 92.7 [[WCPY|WCPT-FM]] in [[Arlington Heights, Illinois|Arlington Heights]], 92.5 [[WCLR (FM)|WCPY]] in [[DeKalb, Illinois|DeKalb]], and 99.9 [[WYHI|WCPQ]] in [[Park Forest, Illinois|Park Forest]].<ref name=\"LaunchNet\">\"[https://www.rbr.com/chicago-am-launches-progressive-talk-network/ Chicago AM launches Progressive Talk network]\", ''Radio & Television Business Report''. October 17, 2008. Retrieved April 28, 2020.</ref><ref>\"In the air\", ''[[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights, Illinois)|Daily Herald]]''. October 23, 2008. Section L & E. p. 5.</ref><ref>Golding, Shenequa A. \"Off the air\", ''[[Daily Southtown]]''. November 5, 2008. p. A17.</ref> On April 29, 2010, WCPT began broadcasting 24 hours a day, although it reduces power to 1,500 watts after sunset so not to interfere with WBAP in Fort Worth.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"[https://www.wbez.org/stories/_/184c3737-6170-4784-8201-639bfb5945b4 Channel 9 cafe closes as new executive menu debuts]\", [[WBEZ]]. April 30, 2010. Retrieved April 28, 2020.</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=http://wcpt820.com:80/pages/pages.php?page=9|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100530145152/http://wcpt820.com:80/pages/pages.php?page=9|title=WCPT 820 AM Now Broadcasts 24 Hours a Day!!|publisher=WCPT|archive-date=May 30, 2010|accessdate=October 2, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"FCC1\"/> On June 2, 2014, WCPT-FM and WCPQ broke away from the simulcast, and 92.5 in DeKalb took the WCPT-FM call sign.<ref>Venta, Lance. \"[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/88564/chicago-liberal-talker-to-shift-fm-signals-to-brokered-polish/ Chicago Liberal Talker to Shift FM Signals to Brokered Polish]\", ''RadioInsight''. May 5, 2014. Retrieved December 2, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn 2016, WCPT's daytime power was increased to 5,800 watts, and its daytime transmitter was moved to Chicago's Jefferson Park neighborhood.<ref name=\"License\">\"[https://licensing.fcc.gov/prod/cdbs/pubacc/Auth_Files/1717086.pdf Federal Communications Commission AM Broadcast Station License]\", FCC.gov. February 17, 2016. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Application2015\">\"[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cdbs/CDBS_Attachment/getattachment.jsp?appn=101683873&qnum=5120&copynum=1&exhcnum=1 Application for Construction Permit Information Radio Station WCPT Willow Springs, Illinois]\", FCC.gov. July 27, 2015. Retrieved December 19, 2018.</ref> In 2018, WCPT-FM was sold to [[Educational Media Foundation]] and became an affiliate of [[K-Love]], a [[Christian contemporary music]] network.<ref>\"[https://news.radio-online.com/cgi-bin/rol.exe/headline_id=b15655 EMF Closes on Acquisition of WCPT/DeKalb IL for $1.6M]\", ''Radio Online''. November 30, 2018. Retrieved December 2, 2018.</ref> Joan Esposito joined WCPT as weekday afternoon host on February 11, 2019.<ref>\"[https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/183797/joan-esposito-gets-afternoon-slot-at-wcpt-chicago Joan Esposito Gets Afternoon Slot At WCPT/Chicago]\", All Access Music Group. February 5, 2019. Retrieved April 28, 2020.</ref> [[Santita Jackson]] joined WCPT as morning drive host on June 3, 2019.<ref>\"[https://chicagocrusader.com/santita-jackson-new-morning-drive-host-on-wcpt-820-am/ Santita Jackson new Morning Drive host On WCPT 820-AM]\", ''[[The Chicago Crusader]]''. May 30, 2019. Retrieved April 28, 2020.</ref>\n\nWCPT airs mostly [[radio syndication|syndicated]] talk programs including those hosted by [[Thom Hartmann]], [[Stephanie Miller]], [[Amy Goodman]] and [[Rick Ungar]].<ref>\"[http://www.wcpt820.com/weekday-schedule/ Weekday Schedule]\", WCPT. Retrieved February 23, 2019.</ref> Local weekday hosts include Santita Jackson in morning [[drive time]] and Joan Esposito in afternoons. World and national news is supplied by [[Associated Press|AP Radio News]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official|http://www.wcpt820.com}}{{AM station data|WCPT}}\n{{Chicago Radio}}\n{{News/Talk Radio Stations in Illinois}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Chicago|CPT]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1923]]\n[[Category:1923 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:News and talk radio stations in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Progressive talk radio station in Willow Springs\u2013Chicago, Illinois}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name = WCPT\n| image = WCPT station logo.PNG\n| city = [[Willow Springs, Illinois]]\n| area = [[Chicago metropolitan area]]\n| branding = '''WCPT 820'''\n| slogan = Chicago's Progressive Talk\n| airdate = {{start date and age|1923|6|23}}\n| frequency = 820 [[Kilohertz|kHz]]\n| former_callsigns = WCBD (1923&ndash;41)<br>WAIT (1941&ndash;86)<br>WCZE (1986&ndash;88)<br>WXEZ (1988&ndash;90)<br>WPNT (1990&ndash;92)<br>WSCR (1992&ndash;97)<br>WYPA (1997&ndash;2001)<br>WCSN (2001&ndash;05)<br>WAIT (2005&ndash;07)\n| former_frequencies = 870 kHz (1923&ndash;28)<br>1080 kHz (1928&ndash;41)<br>1110 kHz (1941)\n| format = [[progressive talk radio|Progressive Talk]]\n| power = 5,800 [[watt]]s (day)<br>2,500 watts (auxiliary day)<br>1,500 watts (night)\n| class = B\n| facility_id = 16849\n| coordinates = {{nowrap|{{coord|41|58|53|N|87|46|20|W|}} (day)}}<br>{{nowrap|{{coord|41|32|30|N|88|2|3|W}} (night/aux)}}\n| owner = [[Newsweb Corporation]]\n| licensee = WYPA, Inc.\n| webcast = [http://player.tritondigital.com/6111 Listen Live]\n| website = {{url|wcpt820.com}}\n| affiliations = [[Westwood One (current)|Westwood One]]<br>[[Pacifica Radio]]<br>[[Associated Press|AP Radio News]]\n| callsign_meaning = \"We're Chicago's Progressive Talk\"\n| sister_stations = [[WAIT (AM)|WAIT]], [[WCPY]], [[WNDZ]], [[WSBC]]\n}}\n\n'''WCPT''' (820 [[AM broadcasting|AM]]) \u2013 branded '''WCPT 820''' \u2013 is a commercial [[progressive talk radio|progressive talk]] [[Radio broadcasting|radio station]] licensed to [[Willow Springs, Illinois|Willow Springs]], [[Illinois]]. Owned by the [[Newsweb Corporation]], the station serves the [[Chicago metropolitan area]]. WCPT is the [[Chicago]] affiliate for [[Pacifica Foundation|Pacifica Radio]], ''[[The Stephanie Miller Show]]'', ''[[Democracy Now!]]'' and ''[[The David Pakman Show]]'', in addition to syndicated personalities [[Thom Hartmann]] and [[Rick Ungar]]; and is the radio home of [[Santita Jackson]]. The studios and daytime transmitter are located in the [[Jefferson Park, Chicago|Jefferson Park]] neighborhood on Chicago's [[Northwest Side, Chicago|Northwest Side]], while the nighttime transmitter resides in nearby [[Joliet, Illinois|Joliet]].<ref name=\"FCC1\">[https://transition.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/amq?list=0&facid=16849 AM Query Results: WCPT], fcc.gov. Retrieved January 4, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"License\" /> Besides a standard [[analog transmission]], WCPT's programming is available online.\n\n==History==\n===WCBD===\nOn June 23, 1923, the station signed on using the call sign WCBD, broadcasting at 870 [[kilocycle]]s.<ref name=\"CoC\">Hearings Before the [[United States Senate Committee on Interstate Commerce]]. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=dIHNAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA127&lpg=PA127#v=onepage&q&f=false Commission on Communications]''. [[United States Government Publishing Office|United States Government Print Office]]. May 8, 1929. p. 126-129. Retrieved August 24, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Kneitel\">\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Popular-Communications/80s/Popular-Communications-1986-06.pdf WCBD, The \"Flat Earth\" Radio Station]\", ''[[Popular Communications]]''. June 1986. p. 31-34. Retrieved October 1, 2018.</ref> The station was located in [[Zion, Illinois]], and was owned by [[Wilbur Glenn Voliva]], who was the \"General Overseer\" of the [[Christian Catholic Apostolic Church]], and was known for his [[flat Earth]] beliefs.<ref name=\"CoC\"/><ref name=\"Kneitel\"/><ref name=\"HistoryCards\">[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/getimportletter_exh.cgi?import_letter_id=46665 History Cards for WCPT], fcc.gov. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref> WCBD was non-commercial, airing [[Christian radio|religious programming]] that reflected Voliva's viewpoints.<ref name=\"Kneitel\"/> The station originally ran at 500 watts.<ref name=\"CoC\"/> On July 14, 1924, its power was increased to 5,000 watts.<ref name=\"CoC\"/> From April 1924 until November 11, 1928, WCBD shared time on its frequency with [[WLS (AM)|WLS]].<ref name=\"CoC\"/><ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/>  In November 1928, its frequency was changed to 1080&nbsp;kHz, where it shared time with [[WMBI (AM)|WMBI]].<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/><ref name=\"CoC\"/>\n\nIn 1936, the station was sold to Gene T. Dyer.<ref name=\"Kneitel\"/> It became a [[commercial radio|commercial]] operation, and aired religious, ethnic, and music programming.<ref name=\"Kneitel\"/><ref>''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-Guide/1937/Radio-Guide-37-05-15.pdf Radio Guide]''. Week ending May 15, 1937. Retrieved October 1, 2018.</ref><ref>''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-Guide/1938/Radio-Guide-38-01-15.pdf Radio Guide]''. Week ending January 15, 1938. Retrieved October 1, 2018.</ref> On April 2, 1937, the station's transmitter and the Christian Catholic Apostolic Church's Shiloh Tabernacle were destroyed in a fire set by a teenager who believed Voliva had swindled his father.<ref>\"[https://newspaperarchive.com/cumberland-evening-times-apr-05-1937-p-1/ Youth Confesses to Firing Tabernacle]\", ''Cumberland Evening Times''. April 5, 1937. p. 1. Retrieved October 1, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Kneitel\"/> Its transmitter site was relocated to [[Addison Township, DuPage County, Illinois|Addison Township]], in what today is part of [[Elmhurst, Illinois]].<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> WCBD shared WMBI's transmitter while its new transmitter was being built.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> Its frequency was changed to 1110&nbsp;kHz in March 1941, as a result of the [[North American Regional Broadcasting Agreement]].<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/>\n\n===WAIT===\nIn 1941, the station's frequency was changed to 820 kHz.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> It ran 5,000 watts, signing off at sunset in [[Dallas]] to protect [[WBAP (AM)|WBAP]] in [[Fort Worth]].<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/>  The call sign was changed to WAIT.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> From 1947 to 1959, the station shared time on Sundays with a new WCBD in [[Zion, Illinois]], which operated on Sundays only.<ref name=\"Kneitel\"/><ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1959/1959-05-25-BC.pdf Media reports]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]]''. May 25, 1959. p. 79. Retrieved October 1, 2018.</ref> In 1948, [[Daddy-O Daylie]] began his radio career on WAIT, hosting a [[jazz]] program on the station.<ref>\"[http://www.thehistorymakers.org/biography/holmes-daddy-o-daylie Holmes 'Daddy-O' Daylie]\", ''The History Makers''. May 29, 2001. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref><ref>Heim, Chris. \"[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1989-02-12-8903040739-story.html Radio Roots]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. February 12, 1989. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> In 1954, the station was sold to Robert Oscar Miller and family.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1954/1954-10-04-BC.pdf Our Respects to Robert Oscar Miller]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting/Telecasting]]''. October 4, 1954. p. 20. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref> In the 1950s, WAIT published a chart of the top 20 popular songs in Chicago.<ref>''[http://las-solanas.com/surveys/WAIT/WAIT_1956-12-24_1.jpg WAIT Platter Pulse]'', WAIT. December 24, 1956. Retrieved October 1, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn 1962, the station was sold to a partnership led by Maurice and Lois Rosenfield, for $1 million.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1962/1962-07-02-BC.pdf Changing hands]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]]''. July 2, 1962. p. 44. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"OConnor\"/> The station adopted a [[beautiful music]] format, which it continued to air through the 1970s.<ref name=\"OConnor\">O'Connor, Richard. (2009). ''[http://www.percyfaithpages.org/A%20Brief%20History%20of%20Beautiful%20Music%20Radio.pdf A Brief History of Beautiful Music Radio]'', Percy Faith Pages. Retrieved September 30, 2018.</ref><ref>\"[https://books.google.com/books?id=SyAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA34#v=onepage&q&f=false Stations By Format]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. October 31, 1964. p. 34. Retrieved January 20, 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://books.google.com/books?id=8TkhAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA2-PA56#v=onepage&q&f=false Catalog of Copyright Entries: Third Series]\", Volume 20, Part 6, Number 1; Maps and Atlases, January - June 1966; ''[[United States Copyright Office|Copyright Office]] - [[Library of Congress|The Library of Congress]]'', [[Washington DC]]: 1967. pp. 56-57. Retrieved September 30, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"79Trib\">\"[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Station-Albums/Chicago-Trib-1979-Mar-About-Chi-Radio.pdf Stations, everywhere: a listeners' guide to the AM and FM bands]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune Magazine]]''. March 4, 1979. p. 34. Retrieved September 30, 2018.</ref> In 1978, WAIT briefly switched to an all talk format, before returning to the beautiful music format it had long aired.<ref name=\"79Trib\"/> In 1979, the station was sold to Century Broadcasting.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1979/BC-1979-05-14.pdf Ownership Changes]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]]''. May 14, 1979. p. 72-73. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref> In 1980, it applied to the [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) for a [[construction permit]] to add nighttime operations at 1,000 watts.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> The station added nighttime operations in 1982, and ran 5,000 watts during the day and 1,000 watts at night.<ref>[http://www.fuzzymemories.tv/index.php?c=1139 WAIT AM 82 - \"Nice 'N Easy Music\"], The Museum of Classic Chicago Television. Retrieved September 30, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"BCYearbook1983\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1983/B-Radio-Ala-Mt-1983-YB.pdf Broadcasting/Cablecasting Yearbook 1983]'', [[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting/Cablecasting]], 1983. p. B-70. Retrieved September 30, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn October 1982, WAIT began airing an [[adult standards]] format branded \"Great Hits\", featuring the hits of the 1940s, 1950s, and 1960s.<ref>Alridge, Ron. \"'Saturday Night' in its death throes?\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. October 18, 1982. Section 2, p. 12.</ref><ref>[[Eric Zorn|Zorn, Eric]]. \"WJJD vs. WAIT: Sounds of war have a big band beat\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. February 20, 1984. pp. 1, 3.</ref><ref>\"[https://books.google.com/books?id=XiQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT14#v=onepage&q&f=false 'Great Hits' Readied for Syndication]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. November 13, 1982. p. 15. Retrieved September 30, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"ChiRadioGuide\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Other-Documments/Chicago_Magazine/Chicago-Radio-Guide-May-1985.pdf Chicago Radio Guide]''. Vol. 1, No. 1. May 1985. Retrieved September 30, 2018.</ref> The station aired ''[[Chuck Schaden]]'s Radio Theatre'' weekday evenings.<ref name=\"ChiRadioGuide\" /> [[Eddie Hubbard]] joined WAIT in 1983, and hosted the morning drive show.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1983/BC-1983-07-%2004.pdf Programming]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable]]''. July 4, 1983. p. 101. Retrieved April 27, 2020.</ref><ref>[[Eric Zorn|Zorn, Eric]]. \"On the radio: Hellyer shoots for old stars\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. February 16, 1984. Section 5, p. 13.</ref>\n\n===Soft AC era===\nOn April 7, 1986, the station began airing a [[Soft Adult Contemporary]] format as \"Cozy\" WCZE, delivered by satellite from [[Transtar Radio Networks]]' \"Format 41\" service.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"'Night owl' Schwartz flaps over split in shift at WGN\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. April 8, 1986. p. 50.</ref><ref name=\"BossTrib\">Boss, Kit; \"[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1986-07-17/features/8602200802_1_satellite-music-network-satellite-programming-affiliate-stations Radio`s Satellite Networks Beam With Success]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. July 17, 1986. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> In April 1988, its call sign was changed to WXEZ, standing for \"Extra Easy\", and it became a [[simulcast]] of [[WSHE-FM|WXEZ-FM]], airing [[easy listening]] music.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"For 'beautiful music' stations, 'EZ' does it\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. April 18, 1988. p. 33.</ref><ref name=\"RadioWaves\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Other-Documments/City-Magazines-Misc/Chicagoland-Radio-Waves-Two-Issues.pdf Chicagoland Radio Waves]'', MediaTies. Summer 1988. Retrieved September 30, 2018.</ref> In 1989, it shifted back to a soft AC format, playing more vocals and fewer instrumentals.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1980s/1989/RR-1989-08-18.pdf WXEZ Moving To Soft AC]\", ''[[Radio & Records]]''. August 18, 1989. pp. 5, 38. Retrieved September 30, 2018.</ref> On November 16, 1990, the station's call sign was changed to WPNT, and it briefly aired a [[hot AC]] format branded \"The Point,\" simulcasting WPNT-FM.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4026716.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505110553/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4026716.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=May 5, 2016|title=To make its 'Point,' 'XEZ will disappear|last=Feder|first=Robert|date=November 15, 1990|newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref> In early January 1991, the station was taken off the air, as its owner disposed of its transmitter site in Elmhurst, Illinois.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"'Zoned' news bits - Ch. 5 to add daily cable cut-ins for suburbs\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. January 3, 1991. p. 53.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-M-Street/M-Street-Journal/M-Street-1991-01.pdf Format Changes]\", ''The M Street Journal''. Vol. 8, No. 1. January 7, 1991. p. 1. Retrieved October 1, 2018.</ref>\n\n===The Score===\n[[File:Former studios of WSCR and WXRT.jpg|thumb|Former studio and transmitter site in Chicago's Cragin neighborhood]]\nIn late 1991, the station was sold to Diamond Broadcasting.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1991/BC-1991-10-14.pdf New All-Sports AM Set for Chicago Debut]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]]''. October 14, 1991. p. 39. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref> On January 2, 1992, it returned to the air from a new site in Chicago's [[Belmont Cragin, Chicago|Cragin]] neighborhood, though without nighttime operations.<ref>[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/comment.pl?Application_id=159584&File_number=BP-19910429AH Public Notice Comment], fcc.gov. Retrieved December 23, 2018.</ref> It became [[WSCR]] \"The Score,\" the first [[sports radio|all-sports station]] in Chicago.<ref>\"[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1990s/1992/RR-1992-01-03.pdf Street Talk]\", ''[[Radio & Records]]'', January 3, 1992. p. 20. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"KickOff\">[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20160505112238/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4088376.html Sports talk station will kick off Jan. 2]\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. December 24, 1991. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> The Score's original hosts included Tom Shaer, [[Dan Jiggetts]] partnered with [[Mike North]], and Dan McNeil.<ref name=\"KickOff\"/> McNeil would later be partnered with [[Terry Boers]].<ref name=\"ScoreHistory\">\"[https://chicago.cbslocal.com/2012/01/03/history-of-the-score-chapter-2/ History Of The Score: Chapter II \u2013 The AM 820 Years]\", [[WBBM-TV|CBS 2 Chicago]]. January 3, 2012. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> Former [[Chicago Bears]] coach [[Mike Ditka]] hosted a weekly show in 1992, and served as an analyst during football season until 1997, when he was hired to coach the [[New Orleans Saints]].<ref name=\"ScoreHistory\"/><ref>[[George Castle (journalist)|Castle, George]] (2006). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=1ANDhC9VbuwC&pg=PA224#v=onepage&q&f=false Baseball and the Media: How Fans Lose in Today's Coverage of the Game]''. [[University of Nebraska Press]]. p. 224. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> In 1995, the station was sold to [[Westinghouse Broadcasting|Group W]], along with [[WXRT]], for $60 million.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1990s/1995/RR-1995-04-21.pdf First- Quarter Trading Up 26%]\", ''[[Radio & Records]]''. April 21, 1995. p. 8. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref> On April 7, 1997, at 2:30 PM, \"The Score\" moved to [[WYLL|1160 AM]].<ref name=\"NewStation\">{{citenews|last=Feder|first=Robert|author-link=Robert Feder|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4395757.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207122515/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4395757.html|title=New station joins Chicago radio dial|newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=April 8, 1997|accessdate=January 27, 2019|archivedate=February 7, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>Hirsley, Michael. \"[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1997-04-04-9704040029-story.html Demand for Ditka May Bring Saints to Chicago - On Radio]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. April 4, 1997. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref>\n\n===WYPA===\nIn early 1997, the station was sold to N. John Douglas's Personal Achievement Radio, Inc. for $7.5 million.<ref>Rathburn, Elizabeth A. \"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1996/BC-1996-11-18.pdf Westinghouse/Infinity make Dallas Trust]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable]]''. November 16, 1996. p. 43. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1997/BC-1997-02-03.pdf Station & Cable Trading]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable]]''. February 3, 1997. p. 48. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref><ref>[https://licensing.fcc.gov/prod/cdbs/pubacc/Auth_Files/238891.pdf Consent to Assignment], fcc.gov. February 26, 1997. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref> On April 7, 1997, it began airing a motivational talk format as \"Personal Achievement Radio\", and its call sign was changed to WYPA.<ref name=\"NewStation\" /> On June 9, 1998, \"Personal Achievement Radio\" moved to [[WNDZ]], and WYPA adopted a Spanish language talk format as an affiliate of \"Radio Unica.\"<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"Soap opera channel to get trial run here\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. June 9, 1998. p. 37.</ref><ref name=\"MStreet61098\">\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-M-Street/M-Street-Journal/M-Street-1998-06.pdf Format Changes & Updates]\", ''The M-Street Journal''. June 10, 1998. Vol. 15 No. 23. p. 1. Retrieved April 28, 2020.</ref> Personalities heard on Radio Unica included [[Pedro Sevcec]], [[Isabel G\u00f3mez-Bassols]], among others.<ref>Sayewitz, Ronni. \"[https://www.bizjournals.com/dallas/stories/1998/06/01/newscolumn1.html Radio Unica hits Metroplex with Spanish all-talk format]\", ''[[Dallas Business Journal]]''. June 1, 1998. Retrieved June 30, 2019.</ref> In 1998, the station's owner, Achievement Radio Holdings, merged with Z-Spanish Media.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1998/BC-1998-07-06.pdf Z-Spanish merging with Achievement Radio Holdings]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable]]''. July 6, 1998. p. 48. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref> On May 15, 1999, Radio Unica moved to 950 [[WNTD]], though it continued to simulcast on WYPA.<ref name=\"Feder51499\">[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"3 radio stations find new spots on the dial\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. May 14, 1999. p. 57.</ref><ref name=\"OneonOne\">Kirk, Jim. \"[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-02-24/business/9902240249_1_radio-unica-one-on-one-sports-station One-On-One Sports Soon Zero For One On AM]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. February 24, 1999. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"MStreet51999\">\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-M-Street/M-Street-Journal/M-Street-1999-05.pdf Format Changes & Updates]\", ''The M Street Journal''. Vol. 16 No. 20. May 19, 1999. p. 2. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> In mid-1999, the station was purchased by Catholic Family Radio for $10.5 million, and on June 9 it began airing a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] talk format.<ref>Kirk, Jim. \"[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-06-27/business/9906270160_1_catholic-family-radio-howard-stern-christian-radio Catholic Radio CEO Keeps The Faith About Family Programming]\", ''Chicago Tribune''. June 27, 1999. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"MStreet62399\">\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-M-Street/M-Street-Journal/M-Street-1999-06.pdf Elsewhere]\", ''The M Street Journal''. Vol. 16, No. 25. June 23, 1999. p. 10. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"MStreet51999\" /><ref>Kirk, Jim. \"[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-05-18/business/0005180047_1_stations-catholic-family-radio-nba-lottery Investor May Rescue Catholic Radio]\", ''Chicago Tribune''. May 18, 2000. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> In April 2000, Catholic Family Radio placed all of its radio stations up for sale, and on May 29, Catholic Family Radio's programming was replaced by [[EWTN Radio]].<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"WBEE-AM will toast 45 years with concert\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. May 30, 2000. p. 37.</ref>\n\n===Newsweb ownership===\n[[File:WCPT's studio building and daytime tower.jpg|thumb|180px|WCPT's studio building and daytime tower]]\nIn early 2001, WYPA was purchased by Newsweb for $10.5 million.<ref>\"[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2001-02-25-0102250533-story.html Hallelujah Chorus]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. February 25, 2001. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> Newsweb's owner, [[Fred Eychaner]], is a significant donor to [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] causes.<ref>Harris, Melissa. \"[http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-xpm-2014-05-01-ct-eychaner-lockett-confidential-0501-biz-20140501-story.html Attention-shy Democratic donor Fred Eychaner opens up]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. May 1, 2014. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Zorn\" />\n\nOn March 1, 2001, [[One on One Sports]] (now known as [[SB Nation Radio]]) moved its programming from [[WAWE|WJKL]] to WYPA, and the station adopted a sports format.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.djheadlines.com/index.php?pid=103|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040514064033/http://www.djheadlines.com/index.php?pid=103|title=Chicago Media Headlines - February|website=DJ Headlines|date=February 26, 2001|archive-date=May 14, 2004|accessdate=October 2, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"MStreet22801\">\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-M-Street/M-Street-Journal/M-Street-2001-02.pdf M Street Bazaar]\", ''The M Street Journal''. Vol. 18, No. 09. February 28, 2001. p. 9. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Feder22201\">Feder, Robert. \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20131031162411/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4586434.html One-on-One sports talk goes to WYPA March 1]\", ''[[Chicago Sun Times]]''. February 22, 2001. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> On March 26, 2001, One-on-One Sports' name was changed to Sporting News Radio, and the station's call sign was changed to WCSN.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"Fox drops Murciano as noon news anchor\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. March 23, 2001. p. 55.</ref><ref name=\"CallSign\" /> Personalities heard on the station included [[Jay Mariotti]],<ref>De Luca, Chris. \"Sox' skid is over - But trade speculation overshadows victory\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. May 25, 2001. p. 96.</ref> [[Chet Coppock]],<ref>[[Chet Coppock|Coppock, Chet]]. \"Simply the Best - When all is said and done, Bears-Packers rivalry has no equal, writes Chet Coppock\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. November 11, 2001. p. 130.</ref> [[Phil Jackson]],<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"Channel 2's weather adds too much hot air\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. February 8, 2002. p. 57.</ref> [[Chet Coppock]],<ref>[[Irv Kupcinet|Kupcinet, Irv]]. \"Kup's Column\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. September 5, 2002. p. 46.</ref> and [[Bruce Murray (sportscaster)|Bruce Murray]].<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"Should politicians help journalists fight battles?\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. July 24, 2002. p. 67.</ref>\n\nIn April 2003, [[Starboard Broadcasting]] began leasing two hours of airtime a day to air the [[Relevant Radio]] Catholic network.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"Who'll sweep the market in May? Just stay tuned\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. April 23, 2003. p. 73.</ref> On December 1, 2003, it began leasing the entire day.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"Catholic network puts faith in radio market\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. November 20, 2003. p. 71.</ref>  On May 3, 2005, the station's call letters were changed back to WAIT when [[WAIT (AM)|WAIT (850 AM)]] launched progressive talk with the new call letters WCPT.<ref name=\"CallSign\">[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=16849&Callsign=WCPT Call Sign History], fcc.gov. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Moveto820\">\"[https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/32466/wcpt-chicago-to-move-to-820-am WCPT/Chicago To Move To 820 AM]\", ''All Access Music Group''. November 8, 2007. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Zorn\">[[Eric Zorn|Zorn, Eric]]. \"[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2005-05-03-0505030001-story.html 'Air America' return may not be a good thing]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. May 2, 2005. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> In October 2007, Relevant Radio moved to WNTD, though it continued to simulcast on WAIT until November 25.<ref name=\"Split\">[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"[https://www.pressreader.com/usa/chicago-sun-times/20071024/282815006882610 Split Personality]\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. October 24, 2007. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref><ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"[https://www.pressreader.com/usa/chicago-sun-times/20071102/282845071657903 Suddenly Santa]\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. November 2, 2007. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref>\n\n====Chicago's Progressive Talk====\nOn November 26, 2007, Chicago's Progressive Talk moved from 850 AM to 820 AM, doubling its power and providing coverage to all of the Chicago metropolitan area.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"'Fix' is finished - Emmis pulls the plug on Q101.1's bold morning show after 14 months\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. November 9, 2007. p. 63.</ref><ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"Meter's stuck - Arbitron bows to industry complaints by delaying new radio ratings system\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. November 27, 2007. p. 47.</ref><ref name=\"Moveto820\"/> The WCPT call letters moved along with the format to 820 AM, and the WAIT call letters returned to 850 AM.<ref name=\"Moveto820\"/><ref name=\"CallSign\"/><ref>[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=53504&Callsign=WAIT Call Sign History], fcc.gov. Retrieved October 2, 2018.</ref> Hosts included [[Ed Schultz]], [[Stephanie Miller]], [[Randi Rhodes]], [[Thom Hartmann]], [[Bill Press]], and [[Robert F. Kennedy Jr.]]<ref>Knight, Bill. \"Broadcaster AM 820 broadens range of voices\", ''[[Pekin Daily Times]]''. December 7, 2007.</ref><ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"Liberal talker forms post-Franken ticket\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. February 7, 2007. p. 63.</ref><ref>[[Phil Rosenthal|Rosenthal, Phil]]. \"[https://newsblogs.chicagotribune.com/towerticker/2008/10/air-america-con.html 'Nine FM' consolidates -- who's left?]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. October 18, 2008. Retrieved April 29, 2020.</ref><ref name=\"LaunchNet\"/> On May 19, 2008, WCPT began airing [[The Rachel Maddow Show (radio program)|The Rachel Maddow Show]].<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"Radio Rachel - MSNBC's star political analyst brings talk show back to WCPT\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. May 16, 2008. p. 49.</ref>\n\nOn March 29, 2008, [[Jake Hartford]] joined WCPT, hosting Saturday mornings.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"It's just Jake - Hartford finds happy landing as Saturday morning host at WCPT\", ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. November 9, 2007. p. 63.</ref> In late October 2008, the station started simulcasting on 92.7 [[WCPY|WCPT-FM]] in [[Arlington Heights, Illinois|Arlington Heights]], 92.5 [[WCLR (FM)|WCPY]] in [[DeKalb, Illinois|DeKalb]], and 99.9 [[WYHI|WCPQ]] in [[Park Forest, Illinois|Park Forest]].<ref name=\"LaunchNet\">\"[https://www.rbr.com/chicago-am-launches-progressive-talk-network/ Chicago AM launches Progressive Talk network]\", ''Radio & Television Business Report''. October 17, 2008. Retrieved April 28, 2020.</ref><ref>\"In the air\", ''[[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights, Illinois)|Daily Herald]]''. October 23, 2008. Section L & E. p. 5.</ref><ref>Golding, Shenequa A. \"Off the air\", ''[[Daily Southtown]]''. November 5, 2008. p. A17.</ref> On April 29, 2010, WCPT began broadcasting 24 hours a day, although it reduces power to 1,500 watts after sunset so not to interfere with WBAP in Fort Worth.<ref>[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]. \"[https://www.wbez.org/stories/_/184c3737-6170-4784-8201-639bfb5945b4 Channel 9 cafe closes as new executive menu debuts]\", [[WBEZ]]. April 30, 2010. Retrieved April 28, 2020.</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=http://wcpt820.com:80/pages/pages.php?page=9|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100530145152/http://wcpt820.com:80/pages/pages.php?page=9|title=WCPT 820 AM Now Broadcasts 24 Hours a Day!!|publisher=WCPT|archive-date=May 30, 2010|accessdate=October 2, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"FCC1\"/> On June 2, 2014, WCPT-FM and WCPQ broke away from the simulcast, and 92.5 in DeKalb took the WCPT-FM call sign.<ref>Venta, Lance. \"[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/88564/chicago-liberal-talker-to-shift-fm-signals-to-brokered-polish/ Chicago Liberal Talker to Shift FM Signals to Brokered Polish]\", ''RadioInsight''. May 5, 2014. Retrieved December 2, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn 2016, WCPT's daytime power was increased to 5,800 watts, and its daytime transmitter was moved to Chicago's Jefferson Park neighborhood.<ref name=\"License\">\"[https://licensing.fcc.gov/prod/cdbs/pubacc/Auth_Files/1717086.pdf Federal Communications Commission AM Broadcast Station License]\", FCC.gov. February 17, 2016. Retrieved October 3, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Application2015\">\"[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cdbs/CDBS_Attachment/getattachment.jsp?appn=101683873&qnum=5120&copynum=1&exhcnum=1 Application for Construction Permit Information Radio Station WCPT Willow Springs, Illinois]\", FCC.gov. July 27, 2015. Retrieved December 19, 2018.</ref> In 2018, WCPT-FM was sold to [[Educational Media Foundation]] and became an affiliate of [[K-Love]], a [[Christian contemporary music]] network.<ref>\"[https://news.radio-online.com/cgi-bin/rol.exe/headline_id=b15655 EMF Closes on Acquisition of WCPT/DeKalb IL for $1.6M]\", ''Radio Online''. November 30, 2018. Retrieved December 2, 2018.</ref> Joan Esposito joined WCPT as weekday afternoon host on February 11, 2019.<ref>\"[https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/183797/joan-esposito-gets-afternoon-slot-at-wcpt-chicago Joan Esposito Gets Afternoon Slot At WCPT/Chicago]\", All Access Music Group. February 5, 2019. Retrieved April 28, 2020.</ref> [[Santita Jackson]] joined WCPT as morning drive host on June 3, 2019.<ref>\"[https://chicagocrusader.com/santita-jackson-new-morning-drive-host-on-wcpt-820-am/ Santita Jackson new Morning Drive host On WCPT 820-AM]\", ''[[The Chicago Crusader]]''. May 30, 2019. Retrieved April 28, 2020.</ref>\n\nWCPT airs mostly [[radio syndication|syndicated]] talk programs including those hosted by [[Thom Hartmann]], [[Stephanie Miller]], [[Amy Goodman]] and [[Rick Ungar]].<ref>\"[http://www.wcpt820.com/weekday-schedule/ Weekday Schedule]\", WCPT. Retrieved February 23, 2019.</ref> Local weekday hosts include Santita Jackson in morning [[drive time]] and Joan Esposito in afternoons. World and national news is supplied by [[Associated Press|AP Radio News]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official|http://www.wcpt820.com}}{{AM station data|WCPT}}\n{{Chicago Radio}}\n{{News/Talk Radio Stations in Illinois}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Chicago|CPT]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1923]]\n[[Category:1923 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:News and talk radio stations in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Tdl1060", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eChicago's Progressive Talk:italics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WCPT_(AM)"}
